# Sustain v1 Product Description

Sustain is a calm focus-training app for people who want more than a basic countdown timer. It turns focus into a simple ritual: choose a mode, set an intention, begin the block, stay with the work, and recover properly when the session ends.

The app is designed to feel quiet, premium, and encouraging. It helps users build focus the same way they build any skill: by showing up consistently, noticing progress, and learning how to recover between efforts.

## What Sustain helps you do

Sustain gives people a structured way to focus, reflect, and improve over time. It helps users:
- start sessions with less friction
- stay with the work instead of bouncing away early
- recognize that the hard start is normal
- recover in a healthy way after each block
- see their focus grow over time

Everything in v1 stays on the device. There is no account to create and no cloud setup required.

## The three focus modes

### Flow
Flow is Sustain’s signature mode. It is built for deeper, more intentional work. Instead of treating the early struggle as a sign to give up, Flow treats it as part of the process.

Why users like it:
- it makes the first hard minutes feel normal
- it encourages them to push through into real concentration
- it frames focus as training, not just time tracking
- it makes longer blocks feel possible over time

Flow is the heart of the app because it is the mode that helps users build focus stamina and recent focus ability.

### Pomodoro
Pomodoro is the familiar focus-and-break rhythm. It gives users a simple, reliable structure for getting started quickly.

Why users like it:
- it is easy to understand
- it works well for shorter work sessions
- it gives the mind a clear cycle of effort and rest
- it lowers the pressure of beginning

### Custom
Custom lets users create their own timing instead of following a fixed pattern.

Why users like it:
- it adapts to different attention spans
- it fits unusual tasks better
- it gives more freedom without losing structure

## The Home screen

Home is the app’s landing place. It is calm, simple, and focused on helping the user begin.

What users see there:
- the hourglass resting at the center
- a greeting and gentle tone
- today’s key stats
- a mode selector
- the main Begin button

How it helps:
- the user can understand the app at a glance
- the next action is always obvious
- the page feels organized instead of busy
- returning to the app never feels overwhelming

## Starting a session

Before each block, users choose what kind of session they want and can add a short intention for the work ahead.

Why that matters:
- it makes the session feel deliberate
- it gives the user a moment to commit
- it turns “I should start” into a clear action

That small step helps the app feel like a real focus ritual rather than a generic timer.

## The live session experience

Once a session begins, the hourglass becomes the center of the screen. The session is meant to feel immersive and steady, not noisy or distracting.

What the session experience does:
- shows the active block clearly
- gives the user a strong visual anchor
- supports cues and transitions
- keeps the focus block feeling protected

How it helps:
- the user always knows where they are in the block
- focus feels more tangible
- the app stays present without getting in the way

## Flow, struggle, and recovery

Sustain is built around the idea that focus happens in stages.

The app acknowledges:
- the struggle at the beginning
- the quieter, deeper middle where flow appears
- the recovery that follows after the block

Why this matters:
- it normalizes the hard part of starting
- it keeps users from mistaking discomfort for failure
- it reminds them that recovery is part of productivity too

This is one of Sustain’s biggest differences. It does not pretend focus is effortless. It helps users work through the resistance honestly.

## The hourglass

The hourglass is the signature visual of the app. It is not just decoration; it gives the whole experience its identity.

What it does:
- represents time and progress visually
- changes with the selected theme
- moves as the session moves
- makes the app feel like a ritual rather than a utility

How it helps:
- the app feels memorable
- users can see their progress instead of only reading it
- focus becomes something they can experience, not just measure

## Focus Score

Focus Score is the app’s main progress number. It shows how strong the user’s recent focus has been on a scale from 0 to 100.

What it means in plain language:
- it reflects recent Flow sessions, not the user’s entire history
- it rises slowly and honestly over time
- one good session helps, but it does not instantly make the user “advanced”
- shorter or weaker sessions have less impact

Why it helps:
- users can see their progress growing
- improvement feels earned
- the number encourages consistency, not perfection

The point of Focus Score is to answer a simple question: how well is the user focusing lately?

## Session Score

Session Score is the score for one Flow session. It is the building block behind Focus Score.

What it captures:
- whether the user finished the block
- whether they stopped early
- whether they pushed beyond the target length
- how strong that single block was in context

Why it matters:
- finishing the block gives the best result
- stopping early lowers the score
- going beyond the target earns a small bonus
- very short false starts do not count

This keeps the app honest. It rewards real focus, not just opening the timer and walking away.

## Focus Stamina

Focus Stamina is the app’s way of describing how long a user can sustainably focus in a single block.

What it does for the user:
- helps them choose a realistic session length
- grows as they prove they can hold focus longer
- keeps them from overestimating where they are today

Why it helps:
- it makes longer sessions feel achievable
- it supports gradual improvement
- it adapts to the user instead of forcing a fixed target

In Sustain, stamina is about demonstrated ability. It grows from real effort and does not punish a short rough session by dragging the number down.

## Focus Average

Focus Average shows the user’s typical session length.

What it tells them:
- how long they usually focus
- whether their sessions are getting longer over time
- what a normal day in the app looks like for them

Why it helps:
- it is an easy number to understand
- it turns progress into something visible
- it gives users another way to measure growth besides streaks

## Today, Streak, and total focus

These are the app’s everyday progress stats.

What they mean:
- Today shows how much focus the user has completed so far today
- Streak shows how many days in a row they’ve kept the habit alive
- Total focus shows all the real focus time they’ve built up over time

Why users care:
- they can see momentum building day by day
- they can tell whether they are staying consistent
- they get quick feedback without needing to dig into charts

These numbers are meant to encourage steady practice, not pressure.

## Other progress records

Sustain also shows supporting records that help users understand their progress from different angles.

These include:
- Sessions completed: how many sessions were finished as planned
- Longest session: the single longest focus session they have ever done
- Best day: the day with the most total focus time
- Highest Focus Score: the best Flow-based score they have reached
- Focusing since: how long they’ve been building the habit

Why these matter:
- they make progress feel personal
- they show both consistency and peak effort
- they help users see the story behind the numbers

## Insights

Insights is the app’s reflection space. It turns the user’s history into a clear picture of their habits.

What it helps users see:
- how their focus changes over time
- when they focus best
- which mode they use most
- how consistent they are
- how their strongest sessions compare to their average ones

Why it helps:
- it turns raw history into useful patterns
- it helps users learn from themselves
- it makes the app feel like a coach, not just a stopwatch

The goal is not to flood the user with numbers. It is to help them notice what actually works.

## Session history

Session history gives users a record of the work they have already done.

What it offers:
- a list of past sessions
- a way to review focus over time
- a reminder of how much effort has already been put in

Why it helps:
- it reinforces consistency
- it gives users a sense of progress they can look back on
- it makes focus feel cumulative instead of fleeting

## Profile

The Profile screen is the user’s personal home inside Sustain.

What it includes:
- a name
- a profile photo
- the Focus Score shown prominently
- total focus, streak, and session count
- links to Insights, history, and the guide

Why it helps:
- it gives the app a personal center
- it makes progress feel owned by the user
- it keeps the important information easy to reach

## Themes

Sustain includes color themes so the app can feel more personal and more beautiful.

What themes do:
- change the look and mood of the app
- update the hourglass and the whole interface together
- give users a free default look and premium alternatives

Why it helps:
- users can choose a style that suits them
- the app feels more like theirs
- the visual experience can stay fresh without changing the core workflow

## Notifications

Notifications are optional and stay under the user’s control.

What they can do:
- remind the user to focus
- send a daily quote or tip
- give a gentle streak reminder
- support live session reminders

Why it helps:
- users can set up the support they want
- the app nudges without becoming intrusive
- reminders feel helpful instead of spammy

## Backup and restore

Sustain includes manual backup and restore so users can protect their data.

What it does:
- lets users save their history to a file
- lets them bring it back later
- helps them move to a new phone without losing progress

Why it helps:
- users keep ownership of their data
- they have a safety net if they switch devices
- the app stays privacy-first while still being practical

## Privacy

Privacy is a core part of the v1 experience.

What that means:
- everything stays on the device
- there are no accounts in v1
- there is no third-party analytics in v1
- there is no crash reporting in v1
- the app works offline-first

Why it helps:
- the app feels safer and calmer
- the user does not have to sign in
- there is less friction and less worry
- the product feels trustworthy by default

## Guide and FAQ

Sustain includes a guide and FAQ so the method is easy to understand.

What they do:
- explain how the app works
- explain why the modes exist
- answer common questions plainly
- help users get more value from the app faster

Why it helps:
- new users can understand the app quickly
- the rules feel clear instead of mysterious
- the experience feels educational, not confusing

## Sound and session cues

Sustain supports optional session sounds.

What they do:
- mark the start, breaks, and end of a session
- make transitions easier to feel
- add a subtle sense of rhythm and presence

Why it helps:
- users know when the session changes state
- the experience feels more tactile
- sound adds structure without noise

## What v1 feels like

Sustain v1 is meant to feel:
- calm
- minimal
- premium
- focused
- private
- encouraging
- smooth and intentional

It is not meant to feel like a noisy dashboard or a pushy productivity app. It is meant to feel like a quiet tool for building a real focus habit.

